urope, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."],"variants":[{"name":"Bridgid","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."]},{"name":"Bridgit","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."]},{"name":"Brigid","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]},{"name":"Brigit","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]},{"name":"Brighid","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Bridget MacBane was born about 1180, in Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland, her father, Dugald MacBane, was 30 and her mother, Mrs Dugald MacEuire, was 26. She had at least 1 son with Sir Dugald Duncan Campbell IInd of Craignish."},"et":{"about 1180–":"umbes 1180–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1199–1250":"1199–1250","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1152":"1152","1250":"1250","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1180–":"noin 1180–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1199–1250":"1199–1250","1152–Male":"1152–Kuollut","1155–Female":"1155–Kuollut","about 1180":"noin 1180","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1152":"1152","1250":"1250","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1180–":"environ 1180–Décédée","1180–Female":"1180–Décédée","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1199–1250":"1199–1250","1152–Male":"1152–Décédé","1155–Female":"1155–Décédée","about 1180":"environ 1180","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","1220":"1